Date:    Fri, 03 Apr 92 11:03:00 +1200
From:    "Mark Aitchison, U of Canty; Physics" <PHYS169@csc.canterbury.ac.nz>
Subject: Re: Heuristic scanner flaws (PC)

CSCRDW%CURIE@epavax.rtpnc.epa.gov (Ron Whittle) writes:
>>From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
>>Incidently, the original SafeMBR.com and its removal tool 2to1.com have been
>>superceeded by the much more capable FixMBR program which does not trip
>>F-Prot 2.02d.
>
>   This posting shows that the heuristic analysis is already flawed,
> and most people haven't even implemented it yet.  If you can write a
> program that will overwrite the MBR and F-Prot 2.02d heuristic scanner
> doesn't trip on it, then a virus could use the same code that you are
> using.

Well, you could say that F-Prot is doing a good job, since SafeMBR is
a good-guy program, so perhaps F-Prot is being very clever in not
reporting it as suspect :-).

Seriously, though, it should be possible to have programs that simply
write to the MBR pass that sort of test - where it should fail is if
the program is part of a boot sector, or at execution time when the
actual contents of what it is writing are checked. However, I'm sure
it is simply much harder to write heuristic scanners to spot such
activities in executable files as opposed to boot sectors.

Since it is also possible (in fact possibly easier) to rewrite a
program to avoid scanners looking for particular byte sequences, you
really have to ask: "Is a heuristic scanner (or mixed method scanner)
going to be better than the conventional string match scanners?" ... I
think the answer is YES!

But I also that such scanners are a long way from the total answer.
It shouldn't come as a surprise to people that scanners aren't
perfect. You have to use them in conjunction with other anti-virus
methods. I expect to see a type of scanner much better than the
up-coming generation of heuristic ones, but even that could not, for
example, pronounce whether Norton's utilities (such as a disk editor)
is a virus or not... only software watching what is happenning can do
that. I am very surprised that such software isn't part of the current
generation of 386-based software.  Instead of a message like "An
application has just corrupted the system area, you'll have to close
down everything and re-boot!" we should be seeing "An application
tried to corrupt memory areas that don't belong to it, do you want me
to nuke it?" (or words to that effect).

(This discussion is getting interesting, at last!)
Bye,
Mark Aitchison.

