Date:    Mon, 06 Apr 92 07:47:11 +0000
From:    nils@f109f.mil.se (Nils Hammar)
Subject: Virus protection in general

One thing that I think stops viruses very efficiently is to use
electrically write-protectable hard disks for the programs, and
regular writeable harddisks for the data and memory swapping. This
will probably be the best way to limit the virus attacks on the hard
disks. The write protection is usually occuring on floppy disks, but
there are a few hard disks that allows it too.  Most minicomputer
disks do it, and a few removable PC disks like the Passport plus
removable media. If we all try to tell the hard disk manufacturers
that we want a write protection option on the hard disks, I think that
they will let us have it as an add-on feature.  This option will be
very welcome at some sites, especially military ones.

